    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA198-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu piṉceṉṟa cevili iṭaiccurattuk kaṇṭārkkuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante encouraged HER who was unable to bear it when the marriage was delayed.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA198">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            cēyiṉ varūu matavali yāvuyarn</l>
<l>            tōmai nīṭiya kāṉiṭai yatta</l>
<l>            muṉṉā ḷumpark kaḻinta veṉmakaḷ</l>
<l>            kaṇpaṭa nīrāḻn taṉṟē tantai</l>
<l>            taṉṉū riṭavayiṟ ṟoḻuvē ṉuṇpal </l>
<l>            kōṭēn talku larumpiya titalai</l>
<l>            vāarn tilaṅkuvā leyiṟṟup polintatārc</l>
<l>            cilvaḷaip palkūn talaḷē yavaḷē</l>
<l>            maiyaṇa leruttiṉ muṉpiṟ ṟaṭakkai</l>
<l>            valvil lampi ṉeyyā vaṇmakiḻt </l>
<l>            tantai taṉṉū rituvē</l>
<l>            yīṉṟēṉ yāṉē polikanum peyarē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>O strong man that comes from a distance, water sank so as to fill [my] eyes<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kaṇ paṭa nīr āḻntaṉṟē</term>: the meaning is clear, but the phrasing seems awkward, since actually <term xml:lang="ta">āḻ</term> is "to sink into something", so we would expect the eyes as subject, which is impossible because of the inf. paṭa (and because of the n.sg. predicate).</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	[because of] my daughter who passed by over there yesterday</l>
<l rend="indent2">	on the road in the midst of the forest where Ōmai trees have grown long</l>
<l rend="indent2">	[and] Yām trees have become high.</l>
<l>I pay homage to the father at the place of his village.<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains this as a particular socially coloured dialogue: the mother would have seen a strange couple when on the look-out for her eloped daughter, and ask the man whether he had seen her own girl. So, the first sentence is supposed to explain that she mistook the strange woman for her daughter and was shaken, while this one would be the respectful address to the husband of that woman (whom she addresses as her father). This sounds strange, but, as often enough, the wording of the poem sounds even more strange without such an explanation. Unfortunately, the alternative line given by ET does not seem to make things better, or at least I fail to understand it. It might be the second part of an address, not only directed to a man, but also to a woman.</note></l>
<l>She, she has many tresses [and] few bangles,</l>
<l rend="indent">	a garland that glittered [and] upright shining pure teeth, beauty spots</l>
<l rend="indent">	that budded on [her] hips with eminent bulk?, fine [and] many.<note place="foot">Inspite of its position there is nothing to be done but to connect <term xml:lang="ta">nuṇpal</term> with <term xml:lang="ta">titalai</term>.</note></l>
<l>This village is [her] father's,</l>
<l rend="indent">	unwearyingly generous with toddy(?), with arrows in [his] strong bow,</l>
<l rend="indent2">  with broad hands, with strength in [his] neck [and] a black beard.</l>
<l>I brought her forth. May your name flourish.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
